1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { Since the pairings went up shortly before the round, it was likely that my opponent didn't have much time to prepare for me. In such cases, I usually default to the London Opening. } 2... d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. Ne5 { A trendy and tricky move } (5. Bg3 { This is the old mainline I used to play several years ago }) 5... O-O 6. Nd2 c5 7. c3 Qc7 8. Bd3 Nbd7 (8... Nc6) 9. Ndf3 c4 10. Bc2 b5 11. h4!? { While this wasn't specific preparation, it is a very typical idea in such positions. } 11... Rb8 12. h5 (12. a3!? { I didn't consider this during the game, but engine likes this move. It's probably to white's benefit to open the a-file if black wants to acheive the b4 break. The following line shows an illustration of this... } 12... a5 13. g4 b4 14. axb4 axb4 15. g5 Nh5 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. Ne5 g6 19. Ra7 $16) 12... h6? 13. g4! Ne4 14. Rg1?? { I thought this was a simple and safe approach to build up the kingside attack, but it misses a big opportunity } (14. g5! { I considered this during the game, but I thought it just lost a pawn. I didn't calculate deeply or accurately enough. In every line, white gets massive compensation with a crushing attack } 14... hxg5 15. Nxg5 Nxg5 16. Bxg5 Nxe5 (16... Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. Bf4 $18) 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. h6 g6 19. f4! $18 { [%csl Ge5] } 19... Bd6 20. h7+ { [%cal Gg8h8,Gg5f6] } 20... Kg7 21. Bh6+) 14... f6 15. Ng6 Re8 16. Nd2 Bb7 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. f4 b4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. g5 bxc3 21. bxc3 hxg5 22. fxg5 (22. h6!? { I didn't go into this because it looked quite murky. However, the following line is a nice example of how white keeps initiative until the attack is decisive. } 22... gxh6 23. Qh5 Kg7 24. Nxc4 Qc7 25. fxg5 fxg5 26. Nge5 Nxe5 27. Nxe5 Qxc3+ 28. Kf2 Rf8+ 29. Kg2 Qb2+ 30. Kh1 Rf6 31. Rxg5+! $18) 22... Qh2 23. Qg4 f5 24. Qg2 Qxg2 25. Rxg2 Bd5 26. O-O-O? { A terrible misjudgement. I wanted to prevent Rb2, but this is not the way to do so. } (26. Nf1 { In hindset, this is so much simpler. With this move, white aims to improve all the pieces and achieve a harmonious and solid setup with Ng3 Rc2 and Kd2 }) 26... Nb6 27. Kc2 Bc6 28. Rb1 Nd5 29. Rxb8 Rxb8 30. Kc1 { This is the only move to survive! At first, it looks counter-intuitive to leave both pawns undefended, but this ensures Nxe3 does not come with check. } 30... Bb5 (30... Nxe3? 31. Ne7+ Kf8 32. Nxc6 $18) 31. Nb1 Nxe3?? (31... Be8! { Apparently this is completely winning, but it's not an easy move to spot }) 32. Rb2 Rb7 33. Na3 Ba6 34. Rxb7 Bxb7 35. Kd2 Ng2 36. Nxc4 f4 37. Ne7+? (37. Nce5 { The only drawing move. It is crucial to control the f7-square before playing Ne7+ } 37... f3 (37... e3+ 38. Ke2) 38. Ne7+ Kf8 39. N7g6+ Kg8 (39... Ke8? 40. h6)) 37... Kf8? (37... Kf7 38. h6 { This was my idea, but it simply fails... } 38... e3+ (38... gxh6 39. gxh6 f3 40. Ne5+ Kxe7 41. h7 e3+ $19) 39. Kd3 Kxe7 40. h7 Be4+!! 41. Kxe4 e2 42. h8=Q e1=Q+ 43. Kf3 Qf1+ 44. Kg4 Qd1+ 45. Kh3 Qh1+ $19) 38. Ng6+ Kg8 39. Ne7+? Kf8? 40. Ng6+ { Draw agreed. I had mixed feelings after this game. On one hand, I could have probably won very quickly out of the opening. On the other hand, my opponent accepted a draw in a position that was winning for him. I guess I was lucky to come away with a half point! } *


